Attending raids is not about getting loot, it's about the guild(s) coming together to assist each other in improving the guild(s).  Yes, when you are fortunate enough to be awarded or win a roll on a nice piece of gear it's a joyous thing, but should be an added bonus, not the highlight of the raid for you.<br>
I'm not pointing fingers here and saying that person x is greedy or loot hungry.  I have not met anyone in DS or OOtBS that I feel is way.  I do realise how easy it is to be caught up in looking things up on the web and imagining how nice that item would be for your character.  I'm a 49 monk and still wearing a serpentine bracer on one wrist...there are many wrist items I've drooled over on the web.<br>
I don't have better for many reasons, I haven't gotten in groups at places these drop, I haven't farmed PP to buy a better one and to be honest, I have a hard time sticking to one of my characters for an extended period of time.  That's a fault I have and therefore I miss out on gear, but I don't miss out on why I play...For the fun.<br>
Well, this has been long winded enough I think.  Let's all try to make what raids we can, reguardless of whether or not we're going to get loot.  If more people pitch in to the alliance raids, the smoother the raids will go, the more drops we'll get and the more raids we'll hold, all increasing the nice drops for everyone.<br>
May Quellious bring peace and tranquility into your lives.<br>
<br>
